StringSequence.definition: A list of strings where the order of the values is fixed. A space separates each value. For example, "one two three".

FloatSequence.definition: A list of floating point numbers where the order of the values is fixed. A space separates each value. For example, "1.2 3.4 5.6".

Value.definition: A description of the standardized measurement increments in which a value is specified. The description is represented as a mathematical phrase. Units should be represented by widely accepted representation. For example, units should conform to the International System of Units (SI) which is maintained by BIPM (Bureau International des Poids et Mesures (see http://www.bipm.fr/ ) when appropriate or use tokens like "Re" to represent units of the Radius of the Earth. Within a phrase the circumflex (^) is used to indicate a power, a star (*) is used to indicate multiplication and a slash (/) division. When symbols are not separated by a mathematical operator, multiplication is assumed. Symbols for base units can be found at: http://www.bipm.fr/en/si/si_brochure/chapter2/2-1/#symbols and those for common derived units can be found at: http://www.bipm.fr/en/si/derived_units/2-2-2.html

Boundary.definition: Parameters that define a region in space.

BackWall.definition: Back wall of the simulation domain by which the plasma flow may exit the simulation.

BoundaryConditions.definition: Parameters associated to the simulation boundaries.

CEF1.definition: Cluster Exchange Format (CEF), version 1, is a self-documenting ASCII format designed for the exchange of data. The metadata contains information compatible with the ISTP recommendations for CDF.

CEF2.definition: Cluster Exchange Format (CEF), version 2, is a self-documenting ASCII format designed for the exchange of data and introduced for Cluster Active Archive. Compared to version 1, the metadata description of vectors and tensors is different.

ChargeExchange.definition: Chemical process involving a charge transfer from an ion (which becomes neutral) to a neutral (which becomes ionized).

ChemicalFormula.definition: Chemical formula representing a population of particle.

CodeLanguage.definition: Language in which a numerical code is written.

CoordinatesLabel.definition: A string list of the labels of each dimension of the spatial domain.

CrossSection.definition: Cross section of the reaction, when the reaction implies the collision of two particles.

DensityProfile.definition: Density profile of the particles in a population.

DiagnosisTimeStep.definition: Time at which a diagnosis is performed and quantity saved.

Dimension.definition: The nnu8mber of items along one axis.

DisplayOutput.definition: A graphical representation of data wherein the underlying numeric values are not (readily) accessible for analysis.. Examples are line plots and spectrograms. A Display Data resource is a type of "data product" which is a set of data that is uniformly processed and formatted, from one or more instruments, typically spanning the full duration of the observations of the relevant instrument(s). A data product may consist of a collection of granules of successive time spans, but may be a single high-level entity.

DissociativeRecombination.definition: Chemical process by which an ion is neutralized by capturing an electron, and splits in two new neutral species.

Distribution.definition: Velocity distribution of the particles in a population.

ElectronImpact.definition: Chemical process by which a neutral is ionized thanks to the energy from the impact of an electron.

ElementBoundary.definition: Parameters associated to the simulation boundaries.

FieldBoundary.definition: Parameters associated with the field boundaries of the simulation.

FieldDimension.definition: Number of field dimensions in the simulation domain.

FieldModel.definition: Field model imposed in the simulation run.

FieldValue.definition: A string list of the values of the input parameter.

FrequencyToGyrofrequencyRatio.definition: The ratio of the characteristic frequency of a medium to gyrofrequency of a particle.

FrontWall.definition: Front wall of the simulation domain by which the plasma flow may be injected.

Ganymede.definition: The biggest moon of Jupiter planet in our solar system.

Granule.definition: Overrides Granule in base schema. An accessible portion of another resource. A Granule may be composed of one or more physical pieces (files) which are considered inseparable. For example, a data storage format that maintains metadata and binary data in separate, but tightly coupled files. Granules should not be used to group files that have simple relationships or which are associated through a parent resource. For example, each file containing a time interval data for a Numerical Data resource would each be considered a Granule. The ParentID of a Granule resource must be a NumericalData resource. The attributes of a Granule supersede the corresponding attributes in the NumericalData resource.

GridCellSize.definition: A string list of the cell sizes in each dimension.

Hybrid.definition: A numerical scheme simulating ions as particles and electrons as a fluid.

InputField.definition: Parameters associated to a field imposed in the simulation

InputLabel.definition: A string list of the labels of each dimension of the input parameter.

InputParameter.definition: A container of information regarding an input parameter of the simulation run.

InputProcess.definition: Parameters associated to a chemical process happening in the simulation

InputTableURL.definition: A URL to a table containing input parameters.

LikelihoodRating.definition: The probability that something is true or possible.

ModelID.definition: A string defining the ID of the model.

ModelURL.definition: URL pointing toward the description of a model used in the definition of a property or an input.

ModelVersion.definition: The version number of the model.

NumericalOutput.definition: Data stored as numerical values in a specified format. A Numerical Data resource is a type of "data product" which is a set of data that is uniformly processed and formatted, from one or more instruments, typically spanning the full duration of the observations of the relevant instrument(s). A data product may consist of a collection of granules of successive time spans, but may be a single high-level entity.

ObjectMass.definition: Mass of an object referenced as a simulated region.

OutputParameters.definition: A container of information regarding the output parameters of the simulation run.

PIC.definition: A numerical scheme simulating ions and electrons as macroparticles.

Paraboloid.definition: A shape generated by the rotation of a parabola around its axis of symmetry.

ParameterQuantity.definition: The value associated with a parameter.

Particle.definition: Overrides Particle in base schema. A description of the types of particles observed in the measurement. This includes both direct observations and inferred observations.

ParticleBoundary.definition: Parameters associated with the particles at the boundaries of the simulation.

Period.definition: A length or era of time.

PhotoIonization.definition: Chemical process by which a neutral is ionized thanks to the energy from a photon.

PlaneNormalVector.definition: A list of the component in each dimension of the vector normal to a plane.

PlanePoint.definition: A list of the component in each dimension of a point in plane.

PopulationChargeState.definition: Charge of a particle in a population, in units of the charge of a proton. Charge state of a bare proton = 1.

PopulationDensity.definition: The number of particles per unit volume.

PopulationFlowSpeed.definition: The rate at which particles or energy is passing through a unit area in a unit time.

Population.definition: A concise description of a particle population, for references.

PopulationMassNumber.definition: The total number of protons and neutrons (together known as nucleons) in an atomic nucleus.

PopulationTemperature.definition: A measure of the kinetic energy of random motion with respect to the average. Temperature is properly defined only for an equilibrium particle distribution (Maxwellian distribution).

ProcessCoeffType.definition: Whether the simulation results are obtained from a stationary solution or are dynamically computed.

ProcessCoefficient.definition: Coefficient associated to a chemical process.

ProcessModel.definition: Model used to describe a chemical process.

ProductionRate.definition: The number of items that can be produced during a given period of time.

Property.definition: A container of information regarding a property of an input parameter.

PropertyLabel.definition: A string list of the labels of each dimension of the property.

PropertyModel.definition: Model used to define a property.

PropertyQuantity.definition: The value associated with a property.

PropertyTableURL.definition: A URL to a table containing  property values.

PropertyValue.definition: A string list of the values of the property.

Radius.definition: The length of a line segment from a center point to the perimeter.

Rate.definition: Reaction rate: reaction production per unit of time.

RegionBegin.definition: The values that define the start point of a region.

RegionEnd.definition: The values that define the ending point of a region.

RegionParameter.definition: Radius of the Region in the simulation.

Remote1AU.definition: A roughly toroidal region that includes the Earth's orbit, but exclusive of the region near the Earth.

SavedQuantity.definition: Quantities that are saved during a given diagnosis.

SideWall.definition: Side walls of the simulation domain.

SimulatedInstrumentID.definition: The identifier of the a simulated instrument description.

SimulatedRegion.definition: The portion of space simulated by the code at the time of a diagnosis. A region is distinguished by certain natural features or physical characteristics. It is the location of the observatory for in situ data, the location or region sensed by remote sensing observatories and the location-of-relevance for parameters that are derived from observational data.

SimulationDomain.definition: Parameters associated to the simulation spatial domain.

SimulationModel.definition: Descriptor of a simulation model: type of numerical scheme, versions,...

SimulationProduct.definition: The type of product produced from the simulation.

SimulationRun.definition: Description of a simulation run, including the code ID, the run spatial and temporal description, and all the relevant inputs.

SimulationTime.definition: Parameters associated to the simulation time.

SimulationType.definition: A characterization of the numerical scheme used in the simulation

Spase.definition: Overrides Spase in the base schema. Space Physics Archive Search and Extract (SPASE). The outermost container or envelope for SPASE metadata. This indicates the start of the SPASE metadata.

SpatialDescription.definition: A characterization of the spatial extent over which the measurement was taken.

SpatialDimension.definition: Number of spatial dimensions in the simulation domain.

SpecificSimulatedRegion.definition: Identifiers for areas of the physical world which may be occupied or observed.

Step.definition: Spatial step between two elements of the diagnosis.

StokesParameters.definition: A set of four parameters (usually called I,Q, U and V) which describe the polarization state of an electromagnetic wave propagating through space.

SubLongitude.definition: The longitude on the surface of an object which is directly below another object.

TemporalDependence.definition: Whether the simulation results are obtained from a stationary solution or are dynamically computed.

TestParticle.definition: A numerical scheme simulating the motion of charged particles in a prescribed field.

TimeStart.definition: Time at which the coverage by the element start.

TimeStop.definition: Time at which the coverage by the element stop.

TotalProductionRate.definition: The total number of items that can be produced during a given period of time.

VelocityDimension.definition: Number of velocity dimensions in the simulation domain.

VersionTag.definition: The text string for a version indicator.

Versions.definition: A container of one or more sets of version information.

ProcCoefType.definition: Whether the simulation results are obtained from a stationary solution or are dynamically computed.

SavedQuantity.definition: Quantities that are saved during a given diagnosis.

SimulatedRegion.definition: Identifiers for areas of the physical world which may be occupied or observed.

SpecificSimulatedRegion.name: SpecificSimulatedRegion
SpecificSimulatedRegion.definition: Identifiers for areas of the physical world which may be occupied or observed.

SimulationType.definition: A characterization of the numerical scheme used in the simulation.
